where $X \triangle S$ denotes the symmetric difference of the sets $X$ and $S$, that is, $X \triangle S= (X\setminus S) \cup (S\setminus X)$. We call $\left\{t_S \ | \ S\subseteq E\right\}$ the set of \emph{(subset-)toggles}.
\end{definition}

\begin{remark}
Note that the single-toggles of Definition~\ref{def:gentoggle} are subset-toggles for which the size of the subset is one.
Also note that the subset-toggle $t_S$ for $|S|>1$ is not, in general, the product of the single-toggles $t_{e_1}t_{e_2}\cdots t_{e_j}$ for $S=\{e_1,\ldots,e_j\}$. In particular, $t_{e_1}t_{e_2}\cdots t_{e_j}(X)$ could be something other than $X\triangle S$ or $X$ if some of the $t_{e_i}$ act as the identity while others do not. The subset-toggle $t_S$ toggles the \emph{entire subset} $S$ all at once (rather than sequentially), if possible, and otherwise acts as the identity.
\end{remark}

We define the power set toggle group as the group generated by all the (subset-)toggles on $\mathcal{L}$.
\begin{definition}
\label{def:powersettoggp}
Let $T_{2^E}(\mathcal{L})$ be the subgroup of the symmetric group $\mathfrak{S}_{\mathcal{L}}$, generated by $\left\{t_S \ | \ S\subseteq E\right\}$. Call $T_{2^E}(\mathcal{L})$ the \emph{power set toggle group} on $\mathcal{L}$.
\end{definition}

The power set toggle group is easy to characterize.
\begin{proposition}
\label{prop:power}
The power set toggle group $T_{2^E}(\mathcal{L})$ equals the symmetric group $\mathfrak{S}_{\mathcal{L}}$.
\end{proposition}

\begin{proof}
To show $T_{2^E}(\mathcal{L})=\mathfrak{S}_{\mathcal{L}}$, we need only show that there exists a subset toggle to take any element of $\mathcal{L}$ to any other. So suppose $X,Y\in \mathcal{L}$. Then we have $t_{X\triangle Y}(X)=Y$.
\end{proof}

One could also construct a toggle group using only some of the subset-toggles.
Such toggle groups are always subgroups of the power set toggle group, since they are defined using a subset of the power set toggle group generators.

\begin{definition}
\label{def:subsettoggp}
Let ${\mathcal{K}}\subseteq 2^E$. Define $T_{{\mathcal{K}}}(\mathcal{L})$ to be the subgroup of $T_{2^E}(\mathcal{L})$
generated by $\left\{t_S \ | \ S\in{\mathcal{K}}\right\}$. Call $T_{{\mathcal{K}}}(\mathcal{L})$ the \emph{${\mathcal{K}}$-toggle subgroup} on $\mathcal{L}$ (or, generically, we call any $T_{{\mathcal{K}}}(\mathcal{L})$ a \emph{subset-toggle group}).
\end{definition}

We define a graph corresponding to each subset-toggle group.

\begin{definition}
Let $E$ be a finite set, and ${\mathcal{K}},\mathcal{L}\subseteq 2^E$. The \emph{subset-toggle graph} $G_{{\mathcal{K}}}(\mathcal{L})$ of $T_{{\mathcal{K}}}(\mathcal{L})$ is defined as the graph with vertices $\mathcal{L}$ and an edge from $X$ to $Y$ whenever there exists a subset $S\in{\mathcal{K}}$ such that $t_{S}(X)=Y$.  
\end{definition}

Note we define a toggle graph rather than the toggle poset of Definition~\ref{def:Lposet}; unlike in the case of the single-toggle group, subset-toggles do not act by simply adding or removing one element. In fact, a subset-toggle may act nontrivially and leave the cardinality of the subset unchanged, as seen in the following example. Thus, you cannot always define a poset by using the subset-toggles as covers.

\begin{example}
\label{ex:togglegraph}
Let $E=\left\{1,2,3\right\}$, 
${\mathcal{K}}=\left\{\{1,2\}, \{1,3\}, \{2,3\}\right\}$, and
$\mathcal{L}=\left\{\{1\}, \{2\}, \{3\}\right\}$. 
Then, for example,
$t_{\{1,2\}}(\{1\})= \{2\}$.
The toggle graph  $G_{{\mathcal{K}}}(\mathcal{L})$ in this case is given in Figure~\ref{fig:togglegraph}.

